'''Dsup''' (contraction of ''damage suppressor'') is a [[DNA]]-associating [[protein]], unique to the [[tardigrade]], that suppresses the occurrence of DNA breaks by radiation.<ref>{{cite journal| pmc=5492148 | pmid=28617314 | doi=10.3390/life7020026 | volume=7 | title=DNA Protection Protein, a Novel Mechanism of Radiation Tolerance: Lessons from Tardigrades | year=2017 | journal=Life (Basel) | last1 = Hashimoto | first1 = T | last2 = Kunieda | first2 = T}}</ref><ref name="motherboard">{{cite web|url=https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/53dkz5/scientists-identify-gene-that-protects-tardigrades-from-radiation|title=Scientists Identify Gene That Protects Tardigrades From Radiation|last=Turk|first=Victoria|date=20 September 2016|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|accessdate=19 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Tauger |first=Nathan |last2= Gill |first2=Victoria |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-37384466 |title=Survival secret of 'Earth's hardiest animal' revealed |work=BBC News |date=20 September 2016 |accessdate=2016-09-21 }}</ref><ref name="Hashimoto et al. 2015">{{cite journal |title=Extremotolerant tardigrade genome and improved radiotolerance of human cultured cells by tardigrade-unique protein |journal=Nature Communications |date=20 September 2015 |last=Hashimoto |first=Takuma | display-authors= etal |volume=7 |doi=10.1038/ncomms12808 |url=http://www.nature.com/ncomms/2016/160920/ncomms12808/full/ncomms12808.html |accessdate=2016-09-21 |page=12808 |pmid=27649274 |pmc=5034306}}</ref> Dsup suppresses X-ray-induced DNA damage by approximately 40% and improves tolerance to radiation.<ref name="Hashimoto et al. 2015" />
Tardigrades can withstand 1,000 times more radiation than other animals,<ref name="Horikawa2006">{{cite journal|last=Horikawa|first=Daiki D.| display-authors= etal|year=2006|title=Radiation tolerance in the tardigrade Milnesium tardigradum.|journal=International Journal of Radiation Biology|volume=82|issue=12|pages=843–848|issn=0955-3002|doi=10.1080/09553000600972956|pmid=17178624}}</ref> median lethal doses of 5,000 [[Gray (unit)|Gy]] (of gamma rays) and 6,200 Gy (of heavy ions) in hydrated animals (5 to 10 Gy could be fatal to a human).<ref name="Horikawa et al. 2006"/> The only explanation found in earlier experiments for this ability was that their lowered water state provides fewer reactants for [[ionizing radiation]].<ref name="Horikawa et al. 2006">{{cite journal|display-authors=8|last=Horikawa|first=Daiki D.|author2=Sakashita, Tetsuya|author3=Katagiri, Chihiro| author4= Watanabe, Masahiko| author5=Kikawada, Takahiro|author6=Nakahara, Yuichi|author7=Hamada, Nobuyuki|author8=Wada, Seiichi|author9=Funayama, Tomoo|author10=Higashi, Seigo| author11= Kobayashi, Yasuhiko| author12= Okuda, Takashi|author13=Kuwabara, Mikinori|title=Radiation tolerance in the tardigrade ''Milnesium tardigradum''|journal=International Journal of Radiation Biology|date=1 January 2006|volume=82|issue=12|pages=843–848|doi=10.1080/09553000600972956|pmid=17178624}}</ref> However, subsequent research found that tardigrades, when hydrated, still remain highly resistant to shortwave [[UV radiation]] in comparison to other animals, and that one factor for this is their ability to efficiently repair damage to their DNA resulting from that exposure.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Horikawa|first=Daiki D.|title=UV Radiation Tolerance of Tardigrades| url= https://astrobiology.nasa.gov/seminars/featured-seminar-channels/early-career-seminars/2012/04/24/uv-radiation-tolerance-of-tardigrades/ |publisher= NASA.com |accessdate= 2013-01-15}}</ref>
The Dsup protein has been tested on other animal cells. Using a culture of human cells that express the Dsup protein, it was found that after X-ray exposure the cells had fewer DNA breaks than control cells.<ref name="motherboard"/>
